International tuna conservation bodies are meeting in Kobe, Japan to address overfishing threatening tuna populations.
Japan, the world's top tuna consumer, faces pressure due to declining stocks.
An international commission reduced bluefin tuna catches, impacting Japan's imports.
The goal is sustainable tuna use, emphasized by Japan's Fisheries Agency.
A global action plan is being developed to monitor and protect tuna populations.
The conference aims to strengthen cooperation among regional organizations to combat overfishing.
The decline in tuna stocks poses a significant threat to marine ecosystems and global fisheries.
Efforts are underway to ensure the responsible management of this valuable resource.
